This paper deals with the tradeoff between privacy and accuracy in decision-making, which is a common topic in the field of computer security (cs.CR). The paper also proposes novel measures of fairness in the context of randomized differentially private algorithms, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The use of U.S. Census data suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the field of computational social science (cs.CY). The empirical investigation of real-world decisions involves data analysis, which is a common theme in the field of data science (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the impact of privacy on decision-making, which is a topic that falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
